iant index funds =0Aand own large chunks of every public company. Roughly s=
peaking, =0A=0A=0A =0A<https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/authors/ARbTQlRLRj=
E/matthew-s-levine=3Fcmpid=3DBBD120224_MONEYSTUFF&utm_medium=3Demail&utm_so=
urce=3Dnewsletter&utm_term=3D241202&utm_campaign=3Dmoneystuff>=0A =0A<https=
://sli.bloomberg.com/click=3Fs=3D825881&stpe=3Ddefault&li=3D11892716&m=3D21=
d6dea82d6b16615cf44233be620525&p=3D12022024>=0A=0A=0A=0AAre index funds ill=
egal=3F=0A=0AThe theory is simple. A handful of big asset managers run gian=
t index funds =0Aand own large chunks of every public company. Roughly spea=
king, the =E2=80=9CBig Three=E2=80=9D =0Amanagers (BlackRock Inc., Vanguard=
 Group and State Street Corp.) togetherown =0A20% or so =0A<https://scholar=
