">This theory is controversial, in part because Big Three index fund manage=
rs do not generally go around=C2=A0<em>saying=C2=A0</em>things like =E2=80=
=9Cwe want our companies to reduce production to have higher profit margins=
.=E2=80=9D They don=E2=80=99t say this in part because that would be an an=
titrust problem, but also because they tend not to think that way. If you r=
un an index fund, it is a bit silly to spend a lot of time analyzing the bu=
sinesses of the companies you own and pushing them to make operational impr=
ovements. You are targeting the index return; whatever the companies do is=
=C2=A0<em>fine</em>, for you, since your job is to reflect their performanc=
e, not improve it. In theory you might be better off if the index return wa=
s higher =E2=80=94=C2=A0more people might buy your funds if stocks always w=
ent up =E2=80=94=C2=A0but that seems pretty indirect, and in practice the m=
ain way you compete, as an index fund manager, is by charging lower fees. I=
t should be very cheap to run an index fund =E2=80=94=C2=A0all you have to =
do is buy a list of stocks and hold them =E2=80=94 so it mostly is. You can=
=E2=80=99t afford to spend a lot of money hiring analysts to tell companies=
 how to improve their performance.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is=
, however, an important exception. The exception sometimes goes by the name=
 =E2=80=9Csystemic stewardship,=E2=80=9D though it is sometimes loosely cal=
led =E2=80=9CESG=E2=80=9D (for environmental, social and governance=C2=A0in=
vesting). The idea is that if you can identify systemic factors that affect=
=C2=A0<em>all=C2=A0</em>of the stocks in your portfolio, then you should pu=
sh companies to improve their performance in those areas. And by =E2=80=9Cs=
ystemic factors=E2=80=9D I mean=C2=A0<em>mostly=C2=A0</em>climate change, t=
hough also some other stuff. But the central intuition does seem to be =E2=
=80=9Cclimate change will cause trouble for all of our companies, so we wan=
t all of our companies to emit less carbon, because that will be good for a=
ll of them.=E2=80=9D This is worth doing for index fund managers because:</=
p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0=
;"> <li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It=E2=80=99s relatively cheap. You ne=
ed fewer people to say =E2=80=9Cglobal warming will be a big problem for a =
lot of companies=E2=80=9D than you would to analyze every company=E2=80=99s=
 operations and suggest specific improvements.</li> <li style=3D"margin-bot=
tom: 5px;">It=E2=80=99s quite scalable. If you own 500 companies, finding a=
 way to improve one company=E2=80=99s performance won=E2=80=99t do that muc=
h for your fund=E2=80=99s returns, but finding a way to improve all 500 com=
panies=E2=80=99 performance will. Again, you are mostly measured against th=
e index return, so improving that return doesn=E2=80=99t help you that much=
, but it helps a little. (Also you are a fiduciary for your clients, so you=
=C2=A0<em>should=C2=A0</em>try to improve the index=E2=80=99s return, if it=
=E2=80=99s relatively easy.)</li> <li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It is =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0or was =E2=80=94=C2=A0good marketing. Low fees are not the=
=C2=A0<em>only=C2=A0</em>way to compete as an index fund manager. Being tho=
ughtful about systemic issues is a way to look like a responsible steward o=
f your clients=E2=80=99 capital, a way to talk to clients about your invest=
ment process that isn=E2=80=99t =E2=80=9Cwell there=E2=80=99s this list of =
stocks and we buy them all.=E2=80=9D And in particular, looking thoughtful =
about=C2=A0<em>climate=C2=A0</em>issues is, or was, a way to attract money =
from clients who are also worried about climate change and want an asset ma=
nager who cares about the issue and pushes companies to pollute less.</li><=
/ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This has changed in recent years, as US Re=
